%I A080597 #38 Jun 18 2026 08:19:41
%S A080597 33,607,8556,99850,1369565,14118313,166100507,1816743913,22445207407,
%T A080597 241641121049,2512258603208,27261146164638,294420436740326
%N A080597 Minimum number of initial terms from the decimal expansion of Pi (A000796) to include every combination of n digits as a substring.
%H A080597 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/ConstantDigitScanning.html">Constant Digit Scanning</a>
%H A080597 Eric Weisstein's World of Mathematics, <a href="https://mathworld.wolfram.com/PiDigits.html">Pi Digits</a>
%F A080597 a(n) = A036903(n) + 1. - _Eric W. Weisstein_, Sep 11 2013
%F A080597 a(n) = A333128(A032510(n)) when A032510(n) has n digits; M(10^n-1) <= a(n) <= M(1.1*10^n), where M(N) = max A333128({0, ..., N}). - _M. F. Hasler_, Jun 15 2026
%e A080597 a(1) = 33 because the digit 0 appears first as the 33rd digit in the decimal expansion of Pi (where 3 is the first digit).
%e A080597 a(2) = 607 because the first 607 digits of Pi contain every conceivable 2-digit subsequence but the first 606 digits do not. The combination (6, 8) appears as 606th and 607th term in A000796.
%Y A080597 Cf. A000796 (decimal expansion of Pi).
%Y A080597 Cf. A036903 (= a(n) - 1).
%Y A080597 Cf. A032510 (last digit string when scanning the decimal expansion of Pi for all n-digit strings).
%Y A080597 Cf. A333128 (position at which ends the first occurrence of n in digits of Pi).
%K A080597 more,nonn,base,changed
%O A080597 1,1
%A A080597 Martin Hasch (martin(AT)mathematik.uni-ulm.de), Feb 23 2003
